{
  "Systole refers to:": "",
  "Heart enlargement": "",
  "Heart arrest": "",
  "Heart relaxation and filling": "",
  "Heart contraction and blood ejection": "",
  "Systole is the phase of the cardiac cycle during which the ventricles contract, generating pressure to eject blood into the pulmonary artery and aorta.": "",
  "Diastole refers to:": "",
  "Heart contraction": "",
  "A heart murmur": "",
  "Heart relaxation and ventricular filling": "",
  "Cardiac arrest": "",
  "Diastole is the phase when the heart muscle relaxes, allowing the ventricles to fill with blood from the atria in preparation for the next contraction.": "",
  "The SA node is called the pacemaker because it:": "",
  "Is an artificial device implanted in the heart": "",
  "Initiates each heartbeat by generating electrical impulses at 60-100 bpm": "",
  "Responds to conscious voluntary control": "",
  "Is located in the ventricle": "",
  "The sinoatrial (SA) node is a cluster of specialized cells in the right atrium that spontaneously depolarizes at the fastest intrinsic rate, setting the pace for the entire heart.": "",
  "The AV node's main role is to:": "",
  "Briefly delay the impulse so atria finish emptying before ventricles contract": "",
  "Initiate the heartbeat before the SA node": "",
  "Speed up conduction to the atria": "",
  "Produce red blood cells": "",
  "The atrioventricular (AV) node introduces a brief delay of about 0.1 seconds in impulse conduction, ensuring that the atria have time to fully contract and empty their blood into the ventricles before ventricular systole begins.": "",
  "On an ECG, the P wave represents:": "",
  "Atrial depolarization (atrial contraction)": "",
  "Ventricular repolarization": "",
  "Ventricular contraction": "",
  "Heart at rest": "",
  "The P wave is the first deflection on the ECG and represents the wave of depolarization spreading across both atria, triggering atrial contraction and blood flow into the ventricles.": "",
  "The QRS complex on an ECG represents:": "",
  "Ventricular depolarization (ventricular contraction)": "",
  "The resting heart between beats": "",
  "Atrial repolarization": "",
  "Atrial depolarization": "",
  "The QRS complex is the largest waveform on the ECG because the ventricles have considerably more muscle mass than the atria, producing a greater electrical signal during depolarization.": "",
  "The T wave on an ECG represents:": "",
  "Ventricular repolarization (ventricles recovering)": "",
  "The T wave represents ventricular repolarization, the electrical recovery phase during which the ventricular muscle cells reset their membrane potential in preparation for the next depolarization cycle.": "",
  "Normal resting heart rate for an adult is:": "",
  "20-40 bpm": "",
  "120-160 bpm": "",
  "200+ bpm": "",
  "60-100 bpm": "",
  "A healthy adult resting heart rate ranges from 60 to 100 beats per minute, though well-conditioned athletes may have resting rates below 60 bpm due to increased cardiac efficiency.": "",
  "The sympathetic nervous system affects heart rate by:": "",
  "Stopping the heart temporarily": "",
  "Decreasing heart rate": "",
  "Having no effect on heart rate": "",
  "Increasing heart rate and contractility": "",
  "The sympathetic nervous system activates the fight-or-flight response by releasing norepinephrine, which increases both heart rate (chronotropy) and contractile force (inotropy) to boost cardiac output during stress or exercise.": "",
  "The parasympathetic nervous system affects heart rate via the vagus nerve by:": "",
  "Increasing heart rate": "",
  "Stopping the heart permanently": "",
  "Having no effect": "",
  "The parasympathetic nervous system, acting through the vagus nerve and releasing acetylcholine, slows heart rate by reducing the firing rate of the SA node, promoting the rest-and-digest state.": "",
  "What is cardiac output (CO)?": "",
  "The blood pressure measured in mmHg": "",
  "The volume of blood pumped by one ventricle per minute, calculated as heart rate multiplied by stroke volume": "",
  "The heart rate measured in beats per minute": "",
  "The total blood volume in the body": "",
  "Cardiac output (CO = HR x SV) represents the total volume of blood pumped by a ventricle each minute, typically about 5 liters per minute at rest, and is a key indicator of overall cardiac performance.": "",
  "What is stroke volume?": "",
  "The heart rate multiplied by blood pressure": "",
  "The total blood volume in the circulatory system": "",
  "The volume of blood pumped by one ventricle per beat, approximately 70 mL": "",
  "The total blood pumped per minute": "",
  "Stroke volume is the difference between end-diastolic volume (blood in the ventricle at the end of filling) and end-systolic volume (blood remaining after contraction), averaging about 70 mL per beat at rest.": "",
  "What is bradycardia?": "",
  "A heart rate above 100 bpm": "",
  "An irregular heart rhythm": "",
  "A heart rate below 60 bpm": "",
  "A normal heart rate of 60-100 bpm": "",
  "Bradycardia is defined as a heart rate below 60 bpm; it can be normal in well-trained athletes but may be pathological if it causes symptoms like dizziness, fatigue, or syncope due to reduced cardiac output.": "",
  "What is tachycardia?": "",
  "A normal resting heart rate": "",
  "A heart with no detectable rhythm": "",
  "Tachycardia is a heart rate exceeding 100 bpm at rest; while it can be a normal response to exercise, fever, or stress, sustained tachycardia at rest may indicate an underlying cardiac or systemic problem.": "",
  "What is atrial fibrillation (AFib)?": "",
  "A normal heart rhythm originating from the SA node": "",
  "A valve disorder causing regurgitation": "",
  "Chaotic, irregular atrial electrical activity producing an irregularly irregular ventricular response": "",
  "A complete cessation of heart activity": "",
  "Atrial fibrillation is the most common sustained cardiac arrhythmia, characterized by rapid, disorganized atrial electrical activity that replaces normal P waves, leading to an irregular ventricular rate and increased risk of blood clots and stroke.": "",
  "What is ventricular fibrillation (VFib)?": "",
  "A normal finding during exercise": "",
  "A slow but regular heart rhythm": "",
  "A mild arrhythmia that resolves on its own": "",
  "A life-threatening arrhythmia with no effective cardiac pumping, causing cardiac arrest": "",
  "Ventricular fibrillation is a lethal arrhythmia in which the ventricles quiver chaotically instead of contracting effectively, producing no cardiac output; it is a medical emergency requiring immediate defibrillation to restore a viable rhythm.": "",
  "What does the Purkinje fiber system do?": "",
  "Rapidly conducts electrical impulses throughout the ventricular walls for synchronized contraction": "",
  "Slows conduction between the atria and ventricles": "",
  "Generates the initial heartbeat impulse": "",
  "Produces hormones that regulate heart rate": "",
  "The Purkinje fibers are a network of specialized conduction cells that rapidly distribute the electrical impulse from the bundle branches throughout the ventricular myocardium, ensuring both ventricles contract in a coordinated, efficient manner.": "",
  "What does 'intercalated disc' mean in cardiac muscle?": "",
  "A layer of connective tissue in the pericardium": "",
  "A type of heart valve between chambers": "",
  "Specialized cell junctions between cardiac muscle cells that contain gap junctions for electrical syncytium": "",
  "The fibrous rings around the heart valves": "",
  "Intercalated discs are unique junctions between cardiac muscle cells containing desmosomes (for mechanical attachment) and gap junctions (for rapid electrical signal transmission), allowing the heart to function as a coordinated electrical syncytium.": "",
  "What is the Bundle of His?": "",
  "A nerve that connects the brain to the heart": "",
  "A group of pacemaker cells in the right atrium": "",
  "A valve that prevents backflow between the ventricles": "",
  "A conduction pathway that transmits impulses from the AV node through the interventricular septum to the bundle branches": "",
  "The Bundle of His is the only normal electrical pathway connecting the atria to the ventricles, conducting impulses from the AV node through the interventricular septum where it divides into left and right bundle branches.": "",
  "What does 'autorhythmicity' mean in cardiac physiology?": "",
  "The regulation of heart rate by hormones only": "",
  "The ability of cardiac cells to generate their own electrical impulses without external stimulation": "",
  "The ability of the heart to change size": "",
  "The heart's dependence on the brain for each heartbeat": "",
  "Autorhythmicity is the intrinsic ability of certain cardiac cells (especially SA node cells) to spontaneously depolarize and generate action potentials without nervous system input, which is why the heart continues to beat even when removed from the body.": "",
  "A well-trained marathon runner has a resting heart rate of 48 bpm but reports no symptoms of dizziness or fatigue. Should this be treated as pathological bradycardia?": "",
  "Yes, any heart rate below 60 bpm requires immediate treatment": "",
  "No, but only because the runner is young": "",
  "Yes, the athlete needs an artificial pacemaker": "",
  "No, athletes often have lower resting rates because their hearts pump more blood per beat (higher stroke volume)": "",
  "Athletic training increases stroke volume through cardiac remodeling, so the heart needs fewer beats per minute to maintain adequate cardiac output; asymptomatic sinus bradycardia in athletes is a normal physiological adaptation, not a disease.": "",
  "A patient in the emergency department collapses and the cardiac monitor shows a chaotic, irregular waveform with no identifiable P waves, QRS complexes, or T waves. What is the rhythm and what is the immediate treatment?": "",
  "Ventricular fibrillation; perform immediate defibrillation": "",
  "Sinus bradycardia; administer atropine": "",
  "Atrial fibrillation; administer blood thinners immediately": "",
  "Normal sinus rhythm; no treatment needed": "",
  "Ventricular fibrillation produces a chaotic ECG with no organized waveforms and no cardiac output; without immediate defibrillation to reset the heart's electrical activity, the patient will die within minutes.": "",
  "A physician calculates that a patient has a heart rate of 80 bpm and a stroke volume of 60 mL. What is this patient's cardiac output, and is it within normal range?": "",
  "480 mL/min, which indicates heart failure": "",
  "140 mL/min, which is dangerously low": "",
  "4,800 mL/min (4.8 L/min), which is within the normal range of about 4-8 L/min": "",
  "8,000 mL/min, which is dangerously high": "",
  "Cardiac output = HR x SV = 80 bpm x 60 mL = 4,800 mL/min (4.8 L/min), which falls within the normal resting range of approximately 4-8 L/min and indicates adequate cardiac function.": "",
  "A patient with a history of atrial fibrillation is prescribed warfarin (a blood thinner). Why does AFib increase the risk of blood clots forming?": "",
  "AFib produces excessive platelets that aggregate spontaneously": "",
  "The atria quiver instead of contracting effectively, allowing blood to stagnate and clot, especially in the left atrial appendage": "",
  "AFib raises blood pressure to levels that damage the endothelium": "",
  "AFib causes the ventricles to pump too forcefully, damaging vessel walls": "",
  "In atrial fibrillation, the atria quiver chaotically instead of contracting, causing blood to pool and stagnate, particularly in the left atrial appendage, creating conditions favorable for thrombus formation that can embolize to the brain causing a stroke.": "",
  "An elderly patient is brought to the ER feeling dizzy and lightheaded. The ECG shows a heart rate of 35 bpm with a normal P-QRS-T pattern. The physician decides to insert a temporary pacemaker. What is the likely diagnosis?": "",
  "Atrial fibrillation": "",
  "Ventricular tachycardia": "",
  "Normal athletic bradycardia": "",
  "Symptomatic sinus bradycardia likely due to SA node dysfunction": "",
  "A heart rate of 35 bpm with symptoms of dizziness indicates symptomatic sinus bradycardia, likely from SA node dysfunction (sick sinus syndrome); because the patient is symptomatic with inadequate cardiac output, a pacemaker is needed to maintain an adequate rate.": "",
  "A nursing student is monitoring a patient and notices that the ECG shows progressively lengthening PR intervals until a QRS complex is dropped. What conduction abnormality is this?": "",
  "First-degree AV block": "",
  "Third-degree (complete) heart block": "",
  "Second-degree AV block, Type I (Wenckebach)": "",
  "Second-degree AV block Type I (Wenckebach) is characterized by progressive prolongation of the PR interval with each successive beat until one impulse is completely blocked and a QRS is 'dropped,' after which the cycle resets.": "",
  "A firefighter responding to a call experiences a sudden surge in heart rate from 72 to 140 bpm. Which division of the autonomic nervous system is responsible for this rapid change?": "",
  "The parasympathetic nervous system via increased vagal tone": "",
  "The somatic nervous system via voluntary muscle control": "",
  "The sympathetic nervous system releasing norepinephrine to increase rate and contractility": "",
  "The enteric nervous system regulating digestive blood flow": "",
  "During the stress response, the sympathetic nervous system releases norepinephrine and the adrenal medulla releases epinephrine, both of which act on the SA node and myocardium to increase heart rate and contractile force, preparing the body for physical exertion.": "",
  "A medical student is learning about the conduction system and asks why the entire ventricle does not contract from the top down. What feature of the conduction system ensures the ventricles contract from the apex upward?": "",
  "The SA node sends signals directly to the ventricular apex": "",
  "The Purkinje fibers distribute the impulse first to the apex, causing contraction to begin at the bottom and squeeze blood upward toward the outflow tracts": "",
  "Gravity pulls the electrical signal downward": "",
  "The AV node delays all impulses equally across the ventricle": "",
  "The bundle branches travel down the interventricular septum and the Purkinje fibers spread from the apex upward, so depolarization begins at the ventricular apex and progresses upward, efficiently squeezing blood toward the semilunar valves and outflow tracts.": "",
  "A patient in the intensive care unit is septic with a heart rate of 130 bpm. Despite the fast rate, cardiac output is low and blood pressure is falling. A cardiologist explains that the heart is not filling adequately. Why does extreme tachycardia reduce cardiac output?": "",
  "The heart valves cannot open fast enough during tachycardia": "",
  "Very fast rates shorten diastole so much that the ventricles have inadequate time to fill, reducing stroke volume": "",
  "Fast heart rates destroy red blood cells, reducing oxygen delivery": "",
  "Tachycardia causes the AV node to block all impulses": "",
  "At very high heart rates, the diastolic filling period becomes critically shortened because more time is spent in systole; with insufficient filling time, end-diastolic volume and stroke volume drop, which can paradoxically reduce cardiac output despite the rapid rate.": "",
  "A paramedic arrives at a scene where a person has collapsed. The AED (automated external defibrillator) analyzes the rhythm and advises a shock. The victim is successfully resuscitated. Why was electrical defibrillation effective in this scenario?": "",
  "The shock directly strengthened the weakened heart muscle": "",
  "The electrical shock simultaneously depolarized all cardiac cells, momentarily stopping the chaotic rhythm so the SA node could resume normal pacemaker function": "",
  "The shock restarted the heart after it had completely stopped": "",
  "The shock destroyed the abnormal cells causing the arrhythmia": "",
  "Defibrillation works by delivering a massive electrical current that depolarizes all myocardial cells simultaneously, resetting the chaotic electrical activity and giving the SA node the opportunity to resume its role as the dominant pacemaker with an organized rhythm.": ""
}